<HL>
   Aztar Posts Loss
   For 2nd Quarter
   Of $25.2 Million
   ----
   By Pauline Yoshihashi
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6A
</SO>
<CO>
   AZTR
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
CASINOS AND GAMBLING (CNO)
</IN>
<LP>
   PHOENIX, Ariz. -- Aztar Corp. said solid second-quarter
performance at its casinos was offset by a $33.6 million
provision for a court judgment, resulting in a net loss of
$25.2 million, or 62 cents a share.
   The company had a net loss of $8.1 million, or 20 cents a
share, a year earlier. Revenue dropped 6.7% to $131.3 million
from $140.7 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Operating profit before net rent nearly tripled to $22.6
million from $8 million, largely because of improved
operating profit at TropWorld, Aztar's Atlantic City, N.J.,
casino. In the face of the opening of a major competitor, the
Taj Mahal casino, TropWorld reported operating profit of
$12.9 million, up from $7.4 million, on a slight decline in
revenue to $78.2 million. Results for the year-earlier
quarter included the write-off of $2.6 million of previously
deferred pre-opening expenses.
   Paul E. Rubeli, the casino operator's president and chief
executive officer, said cutbacks in bus-patron business and
the elimination of other marginal business contributed to
improved operating profits in Atlantic City. In Nevada, the
Las Vegas Tropicana and the Ramada Express in Laughlin both
posted improved operating income in the face of expanded
competition.
   The quarter included an extraordinary charge of $3.5
million to reverse a first-quarter extraordinary gain from
using a portion of a 1989 net operating loss carry-forward.
The prior-year quarter included a $5 million loss for the
closing of a Reno, Nev., casino and expenses of $1.3 million
from the company's restructuring.
   The legal judgment involved the 1979 purchase of the
Tropicana by Ramada Inc., Aztar's predecessor. On July 3, the
Nevada Supreme Court upheld a lower court's decision awarding
Hotel Conquistador Inc. and its holders $14,225,000 with
14.5% interest from January 1982, plus attorney's fees and
other costs. Aztar said it will petition for a rehearing.
   For the six months, Aztar posted a net loss of $15.9
million, or 40 cents a share, compared with a net loss of
$26.7 million, or 67 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue
fell to $256.4 million from $259.2 million.
   John Uphoff, an analyst with Raymond James &amp; Co., said the
results reflect well on Aztar's ability to control costs and
improve margins in the face of major new competitors.
   The company also said it bought back about 700,000 common
shares, or 35% of the two million shares in a repurchase
authorization approved in May. Aztar has about 40.8 million
common shares outstanding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900723-0131
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900723-0131.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Dynatech Set to Post Renewed Growth
   In Sales, Profit for Fiscal First Quarter
   ----
   By John R. Wilke
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5C
</SO>
<CO>
   DYTC
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
</IN>
<LP>
   Dynatech Corp. expects to report renewed sales and
earnings growth for the fiscal first quarter, John F. Reno,
executive vice president and chief operating officer, said.
   The Burlington, Mass.-based technology company will report
per-share earnings for the June quarter roughly midway in the
range of analysts' estimates of 37 cents to 50 cents, on
sales of $115 million to $120 million, Mr. Reno said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A year earlier, net income was $3.9 million, or 37 cents a
share on a larger base of shares, on sales of $102.8 million.
"The first quarter will show a nice increase over last year,
and that we've regained momentum," Mr. Reno said. He sees
steady growth in sales and income for the year.
   Dynatech, which is scheduled to report first-quarter
results at its annual meeting today, owns dozens of
businesses in communications, medical diagnostics, scientific
and consumer markets. The company extends broad autonomy to
its operating units, employing just 35 people in its
corporate offices.
   Mr. Reno said in an interview that the company has
acquired two new businesses, increasing its portfolio of
operating units to 42.
   Dynatech began diversifying from its base in medical
diagnostics and data communications in the early 1980s, with
acquisitions in electronic parts manufacturing,
auto-emissions test equipment, communications test gear, and
weather sensors, including lightning detectors. Its
best-known business is the consumer products unit, Whistler,
which sells auto radar detectors and marine electronics.
   More recently, Dynatech has moved into software and
geophysical and environmental test systems. Also recently,
Whistler unveiled new consumer products, including a
collision avoidance device for trucks that warns when
obstacles or cars approach the driver's blind side.
   Communications is Dynatech's largest business, says
Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. analyst Danielle Danese. She estimates
communications accounted for about $75 million in sales in
the fourth quarter, growing at a 20% clip year-over-year.
Medical and diagnostic product lines were a $15 million
business growing at just 6%, while scientific instruments
grew 25%, to about $27 million. She was cautious on the
stock's prospects in a recent report, issuing a "neutral"
rating pending a pickup in earnings momentum.
   Mr. Reno said that military product lines such as
electronic parts were growing slowly and that Dynatech was
trying to shift some of that technology to commercial
markets. But he said overall profit margins improved during
the first quarter, and cash flow per share increased. Cash
flow from operations rose 12% in the last fiscal year, and
Dynatech stock is currently trading at less than five times
operating cash flow per share, Mr. Reno said.
   Since December 1988, the company has spent about $50
million buying its own stock, narrowing the number of shares
outstanding by nearly three million, or about 25%, leaving
about 9.7 million shares outstanding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
