<HL>
   `Dear Buyer: Sorry Your Widget
   Broke, but It's a Nice Day and...'
   ----
   By Robin Goldwyn Blumenthal
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<LP>
   It ain't necessarily so that the customer's always right.
The old adage has been given new meaning by a contest to find
the best written response to a consumer complaint.
   In bestowing its "Silver Pen" award, the Major Appliance
Consumer Action Panel, a nonprofit mediation board sponsored
by the Association of Home Appliance Manufacturers, considers
such qualities as sensitivity and responsiveness to a
consumer's situation and complaint. Clear and concise
language and proper writing style also are de rigueur.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   What the letter doesn't have to do is give the consumer
what he or she wants.
   Indeed, say experts in the field of consumer relations,
it's not what you tell consumers that counts, but how you
tell it.
   "You tell people to go to hell in such a way that they
look forward to the trip," John Goodman, president of
Technical Assistance Research Programs, quotes one of his
trainers as saying.
   Complaining consumers who fail to receive a satisfactory
response from a company that participates voluntarily in the
program may write to the panel and ask it to review the
complaint. The panel also forwards letters it gets directly
to a company and gives it time to respond. The panel's
recommendations aren't binding.
   Marian Stamos, who runs the well-regarded program, says
the reason the award doesn't require that consumers get what
they seek is simple: "Consumers may not be right in what they
want."
   The panel's 1989 Silver Pen award went to Julie Cicero
Bezotte, customer-service manager at Emerson Electric Co.'s
InSink-Erator division, a garbage-disposal company and
dishwasher marketer.
   Ms. Bezotte's letter responded to one by an engineer who
complained about his dishwasher. "He was listening to it,"
Ms. Bezotte says, and he thought the water in the unit might
not be clean.
   The letter, which is exceedingly cordial, won't get any
prizes for liveliness. But then, nobody would expect a
detailed description of a dishwasher's timer sequence to set
the world on fire. Ms. Bezotte cautioned the consumer not to
"confuse the `wash' cycle and the `purge' cycle." And, she
wrote, "as long as all plumbing and drain connections are
correct, waste water cannot back up into the dishwasher."
   The world will have to take it on faith that the letter
satisfied his complaint. Both the company and the panel
prefer to keep the identity of consumers confidential.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900723-0114
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900723-0114.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Foreign Exchange:
   Any Buying Interest in Yen Soon Fizzles
   As Currency Is Hurt by Capital Outflows
   ----
   By Candace Cumberbatch
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST CANDA EUROP JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The yen has been behaving like a soggy
firecracker: Any buying interest that has flared up has
fizzled quickly.
   That's because the yen is still hindered by capital
outflows from Japan and concerns about Japanese inflationary
pressures -- even though investors are warming up to the
currency, some economists say.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The yen has come a long way from its trough, {but} it
hasn't been a sensational rally," says Lawrence Krohn, a
senior economist at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. He believes
it will take a while for the yen to get up a "good head of
steam."
   When dealings finished here Friday, the dollar was quoted
at 148.60 yen, moderately higher than 148.10 at Thursday's
close.
   In Tokyo Monday, the dollar was trading at 148.20 yen soon
after the opening; it closed at 148.30 yen in Tokyo Friday.
Meanwhile, the U.S. currency was trading at about 1.6330
marks, down from Tokyo's Friday's close of 1.6378 marks.
   In non-dollar trading, the mark and Swiss franc finished
the week at 90.80 and 106.07 yen, respectively, up from 90.25
and 105.38 yen late Thursday.
   While the yen's performance wasn't impressive Friday, the
longer-term picture is brighter. The dollar is down about
7.3% from the 39-month high of 160.30 yen hit April 2; since
early May, the yen has risen approximately 5.5% against the
mark and the Swiss franc.
   Between February and April, the yen was caught in a
downward spiral because of the dive in the Japanese stock and
bond markets and the foreign exchange market's disappointment
with Japan's relatively low interest rates.
   The drop came to a halt after the Japanese financial
markets stabilized and higher Japanese rates lured investors.
   But capital outflows from Japan are offsetting those
bullish influences, economists say. In May, net long-term
capital outflows from Japan totaled $5.6 billion, slightly
more than $5.3 billion in April but less than this year's
high of $7.9 billion in February.
   "The capital flows haven't dropped off that much. They
{the Japanese} have a sustained desire to diversify" their
portfolios, says David Hale, chief economist at Kemper
Financial Services Inc. in Chicago.
   Because yen-denominated investments remain pricey despite
the selling binge earlier this year, Japanese investors favor
less expensive West German, Canadian and Australian assets,
he says.
   With growing interest in the financial markets of West
Germany and other Western European nations, the U.S. markets
are no longer the clear favorite of the Japanese, economists
say.
   Although Japan's inflation rate is relatively low compared
with the rates in other major industrial nations, worries
about building price pressures are still making investors "a
little bit leery" about putting capital in Japan, says
Michael Moran, chief economist at Daiwa Securities America
Inc.
   Japan's broadly defined money supply grew at an average
rate of 12.6% in June from the year-earlier level,
accelerating at a double-digit rate for the seventh month in
a row. The June rate was, however, off substantially from the
13.2% rate in April and May.
   The Bank of Japan predicts the money supply will expand at
rates around 12% in the third quarter, slower than the 13%
average in the second quarter. The central bank's governor,
Yasushi Mieno, said recently that the rapid money supply
growth is due to temporary and special factors, such as the
liberalization of Japanese interest rates.
   Inflation worries have weighed on the yen for some time
even though the Bank of Japan has maintained a tight monetary
policy. The Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development forecasts that Japan's inflation rate will run
about 2.7% this year, much higher than 1.5% in 1989.
   Although the yen has drawbacks, it is expected to keep
working its way up in coming months with help from the higher
Japanese interest rates.
   Yen money market rates have been on the rise recently, and
there is widespread speculation that the Bank of Japan will
soon raise its 5.25% discount rate, possibly in September.
   The yen aside, traders say the dollar will probably
continue to trade within a range for the time being as market
participants wait for fresh news about the U.S. economy and
the budget negotiations in Washington.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York Friday, gold for
current delivery settled at $361.30 an ounce, down 10 cents.
Estimated volume was a light two million ounces.
   In early trading in Hong Kong Monday, gold was quoted at
$361.45 an ounce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900723-0113
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900723-0113.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Commodities:
   Production, Refining and Shipping Problems
   In Central Africa Are Pushing Up Price of Cobalt
   ----
   By Neil Behrmann
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   AFRIC
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
PETROLEUM (PET)
COMMODITY MARKETS FOR METALS (MIN)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Resistance against one-party rule in central
Africa is pushing up the price of cobalt, an important
strategic metal.
   In only the past three weeks, the price surged to $10.50 a
pound from $7.80 because of acute production, refining and
shipping problems in Zaire and Zambia, says Oscar Prager,
managing director of Ayrton &amp; Partners Ltd., London metal
dealers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Cobalt is an integral part of "super alloys" used in
military and civil jet engines and in machine tools. It is
strong, corrosion-resistant and able to withstand very high
temperatures, analysts say.
   It is "strategic" because such things as jet engines can't
be built without it. About two-thirds of normal annual world
cobalt supplies of around 20,000 metric tons is mined as a
byproduct of copper in politically unstable Zambia and Zaire,
Mr. Prager says. He estimates that supplies from these two
landlocked countries could fall as much as 4,000 tons short
of normal.
   Production difficulties are the result of deteriorating
conditions in the economies of the two nations, says Gavin
Sanderson, chief executive officer of China Industrial
Resources, a London metals company, adding that Chinese and
Eastern European industries were buyers of scarce cobalt.
   Moreover, skilled expatriate technical and administrative
managers left Zaire and Zambia in recent months, Mr.
Sanderson says. An attempted coup in Zambia and fighting in
the mineral-rich Shaba province of Zaire are discouraging
foreign personnel from working there, he says.
   "The shortage could be critical," Mr. Sanderson says.
Central African output has fallen in recent years because of
depressed prices, he says.
   But mines and refineries won't be in a position to raise
production markedly, Mr. Sanderson says. There hasn't been
sufficient maintenance to raise capacity, and they won't
attract replacements of foreign qualified staff. They fear
tribal strife if President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire and
Zambian president Kenneth Kaunda are deposed, Mr. Sanderson
says.
   In 1978, an invasion of Zaire's Shaba province
precipitated a ballooning of cobalt's price to $50 a pound
from $7, dealers recall. The price then slumped to around $4
as mines raised output rapidly and speculators dumped stocks.
   Prices could rise sharply again, unless metal is released
from consumer inventories or the U.S. National Defense
Stockpile, Mr. Prager of Ayrton &amp; Partners says. The U.S. has
built up a cobalt stockpile of around 24,000 tons, equivalent
to about 14 months of world consumption, as an insurance
against political or other disruptions, officials say.
   It is included with 91 other commodities in a $10 billion
stockpile. But stocks of cobalt will only be released for
defense purposes and won't be sold if there is a shortage in
the markets, the officials say. Meanwhile, the U.S. is
upgrading the quality of cobalt in its stockpile, and its
long-term goal is to raise inventories to 38,000 metric tons.
   But Phillip Crowson, chief economist of RTZ Corp., a major
international mining company, contends metals merchants are
being alarmists about cobalt. Fears of short supplies of
strategic metals arise periodically, he says, but there are
large stocks of metal world-wide.
   Moreover, the defense industry, a major user of cobalt, is
likely to cut back purchases of cobalt because of detente
between the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and the Warsaw
Pact, analysts say.
   Cobalt is traded in a narrow, illiquid market, dealers
say, which means speculators can drive prices up or down
rapidly.
   Rhodium, another strategic metal, which is used in
automobiles to reduce pollution, is a prime example, Mr.
Crowson says. Prices rose to a peak of $7,350 an ounce early
July from $1,250 a year earlier because of supply disruptions
at a refinery of South African producer Rustenburg Platinum
Mines Ltd. The price then fell to $4,300 an ounce early this
week and bounced back to $5,000 on Friday on extremely low
volumes, dealers say.
   Rhodium supplies are likely to rise in coming months, say
Barry Davison, managing director of Rustenburg Platinum
Mines, who insists that the mine's refinery has overcome its
problems.
   Although rhodium has risen swiftly because of a temporary
shortage, the price could easily tumble when more supplies
hit an illiquid market, dealers say. The same applies to
cobalt.
   Looking ahead to commodity markets this week:
                                                                                                       

   Livestock and Meats
                                                                                                       

   After the close of trading Friday, the Agriculture
Department reported that the number of cattle on feedlots in
13 major ranch states on July 1 rose 1% from a year earlier.
   The report was in line with the expectations of analysts.
   The department reported that the number of young cattle
placed on feedlots for fattening in the second quarter
dropped 2% while sales by feedlots to slaughterhouses were
flat.
   According to analysts, heavy rains this spring improved
the condition of pastures, which in turn reduced pressure on
ranchers to sell their cattle to feedlots.
   On Friday, the Agriculture Department is slated to release
a survey of the nation's cattle herd, which began to slowly
rebound last year after slipping to its smallest number since
1961.
   Industry analysts expect the government to report that the
number of cattle is increasing slightly.
   In the hog market, traders will watch whether pork belly
prices recover from last week's plunge. The price decline was
fanned by speculation that high retail prices are damping
consumer demand. Pork bellies are used to make bacon.
                                                                                                       

   Energy
                                                                                                       

   Crude oil prices soared Friday on the belief that members
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would
toe the line in the face of Saddam Hussein's strong-man
tactics. For the first time in almost two months crude for
August delivery broke through a resistance level and finished
trading at more than $19 a barrel.
   With oil ministers preparing to sit down and talk in
Geneva on Wednesday, traders say they don't want to be caught
short in the market. Iraq's threat to discipline cartel
members who are pumping beyond their quota may cause OPEC
producers to rein in output to no more than 22.5 million
barrels a day. That level is still above the overall OPEC
quota, but far below real OPEC production in recent months.
   Demand for the cartel's crude is expected to increase
during the third and fourth quarter on a seasonal basis,
another factor that will bring some relief to a market
glutted with crude supplies, experts say.
                                                                                                       

   Copper
                                                                                                       

   Futures prices Friday rose almost two cents a pound; the
September contract closed at $1.1980. Traders will be
watching to see if the gains are sustained.
   Friday's advance was a rebound from five consecutive days
of declines, which saw the September price drop 6.15 cents.
The rally occurred despite a 15,000-ton increase in London
Metal Exchange copper warehouse stocks and a tentative
settlement of the Asarco strike that began July 1.
   However, the stock increase had been predicted, and a
labor settlement had been expected after Asarco and the
United Steelworkers union sat down Friday for the first time
since July 3 to resume contract negotiations. Basically,
analysts said, the selling pressure just seemed to have run
its course.
   The copper industry is behaving normally this summer, in
contrast to the past two years when demand for copper was
strong and prices were high, according to Fred D'Agostino,
president of Metal Resources Inc., of Riverside, Conn., a
scrap and refined copper trading firm.
   "Brass, tube and wire mills this summer are closing down
for their regular overhauls, which is leading to a lack of
demand for copper," he said. "Japan, on the other hand, for
several months has been a major buyer of U.S. copper and this
has contributed an underlying support to the market."
   There have been spurts of buying, such as early in the
month when the July contract rose 20 cents on no discernible
reason, Mr. D'Agostino said. "If that demand were to come in
August and September for fourth quarter consumption, I could
understand it. Maybe speculators see something the rest of us
don't," he said.
</TEXT>
