<HL>
   Export Orders Decline
   For Taiwan's Products
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5D
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan -- Export orders for Taiwanese products in
June eased to $5.56 billion, down 7.4% from the previous
month, a government agency said.
   The figures also registered a drop of 2.3% from the
year-earlier $5.69 billion, according to the Economics
Ministry.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Officials attributed the month-to-month drop to a cut in
machinery orders as well as those for home appliances and
transportation equipment. Machinery orders totaled $468
million, a decrease of 19% from the previous month.
   Transportation orders fell to $320 million in June from
May's $397 million. Home-appliance orders fell 45% to $100
million.
   Export orders from January through June amounted to $33.29
billion, down 0.9% from the year-earlier period.
   The U.S. remained the leading destination for Taiwanese
exports, accounting for orders valued at $2.04 billion in
June, down 14% from May and down 9.5% from June 1989.
   European countries ranked second among buyers of Taiwanese
goods. Those orders in June stood at $865 million, against
May's $864 million and June 1989's $820 million.
   Orders from Japan were valued at $786 million, a gain of
4.4% from May but down 6.4% from the year-earlier period.
   Hong Kong ranked fourth among buyers, with orders valued
at $569 million. The figure was a drop of $60 million from
May but a gain of $152 million from June 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900723-0085
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900723-0085.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   BASF Says Workers
   Accounted For in Blast
   At Cincinnati Plant
</HL>
<DATE>
07/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   G.BAS
</CO>
<IN>
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<LP>
   PARSIPPANY, N.J. -- BASF Corp. said it has accounted for
all employees at a Cincinnati chemical plant where an
explosion and fire killed one person and injured 73 others,
mostly BASF employees. But it said it hasn't yet been able to
estimate damage to the plant.
   A spokesman said BASF has set up a center to provide
support and counseling for employees and neighbors at a hotel
in Cincinnati. The company, a subsidiary of West Germany's
BASF AG, said it also is opening a claims office at Xavier
University.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The explosion at the coatings and resins facility killed a
maintenance worker, Lawrence Krechting, a 55-year-old
resident of Norwood, Ohio. Four of the injured were hurt
critically, Cincinnati police said. Initial reports said 63
people were injured and at least one person was missing.
   The facility makes resins, as well as coatings for paper
and for containers such as beverage cans. The company said it
is investigating the incident along with the federal
Occupational Safety and Health Administration; it suspects
the explosion and fire started in the resin building.
   Air-quality tests show that environmental hazards to
residents are low, BASF said. But "damage to the plant is
serious," and production won't resume for "a considerable
period," BASF said. Customer orders shouldn't be affected
because they will be handled by other BASF plants, BASF said.
</TEXT>
