<LP>
   EASTERN AIRLINES would be liquidated under a proposal
expected to be made today by Alfred Checchi, Northwest
Airlines' chairman. Northwest would take over certain assets,
including planes, airport gates and maintenance facilities.
It would offer to broker the sale of the rest to benefit
Eastern's creditors, people familiar with the plan said.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A major guarantor of loans in the student-aid program, the
Higher Education Assistance Foundation, is facing possible
financial collapse, raising doubts about the soundness of its
$9.6 billion in loan guarantees.
   ---
   American Brands agreed to buy Moen Group from Forstmann
Little for $975 million, sharpening the focus of its
home-improvement business. American Brands also posted a 32%
rise in second-quarter profit.
   ---
   Lockheed's contract to build P-7 anti-submarine aircraft
was terminated by the Navy after the company refused to
accept production losses it says could have topped $300
million.
   ---
   Chrysler offered union employees part ownership of the
company and incentive payments in return for helping the auto
maker slash costs.
   ---
   McDonald's failed to meet Wall Street's earnings
expectations and said it is considering new menu strategies
to attract customers.
   ---
   Boeing is holding discussions with Aeritalia of Italy and
Aerospatiale of France about selling its unprofitable de
Havilland commuter airplane unit.
   ---
   Grumman's ex-chairman has drawn the attention of
investigators conducting an inquiry into Pentagon contracting
fraud. But John O'Brien, who resigned suddenly last week,
isn't believed to be a target of the probe.
   ---
   The bidding war heated up for Ford Motor's aerospace
subsidiary, as a consortium headed by Westinghouse promised
not to dismantle the unit if its bid is successful.
   ---
   Compaq plans to introduce today three powerful personal
computers, even though sales of its Systempro 386 personal
computer have been slow.
   ---
   Time Warner may convert Life magazine from a monthly to a
weekly, overhaul its content and switch to a standard
magazine size.
   ---
   Manville's reorganization was placed under the control of
federal Judge Jack B. Weinstein, who has criticized the
financing of the firm's asbestos personal-injury trust.
   ---
   The Philadelphia Stock Exchange is close to signing a pact
with the Frankfurt Stock Exchange to trade warrants on a
German stock index.
   ---
   Texas Instruments profit tumbled in the second quarter,
largely because of lower prices for semiconductor memory
chips. The firm also warned that it might post a
third-quarter loss.
   ---
   Citicorp eliminated two management layers in its
commercial and investment banking unit for North America,
Europe and Japan as part of an effort to trim expenses.
   ---
   Disney settled EPA allegations that the company illegally
dumped hazardous paint thinner and other cleaning solvents
used at Disneyland.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 177,810,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2961.14, off 32.67; transportation 1159.31, off 13.32;
utilities 202.15, off 1.38.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3433.51, up
8.61.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 130.45, off 0.70;
spot index 131.16, off 0.83.
   Dollar: 148.60 yen, up 0.50; 1.6365 marks, off 0.0045.
