<HL>
   Business Brief -- Angeles Corp.:
   Pact Set to Acquire Option
   To Buy Back a 22% Stake
</HL>
<DATE>
07/23/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8
</SO>
<CO>
   ANG
</CO>
<IN>
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Angeles Corp. said it agreed in principle to acquire for
$30 million a three-year option to buy 22% of its common
stock and other securities from certain former owners of
Quinoco Cos., an oil and gas concern.
   The securities were issued to the former owners as part of
a $50 million acquisition of Quinoco in 1984. Angeles sold
the Quinoco oil and gas businesses and related businesses to
Hallwood Energy Partners of Dallas for about $26 million in
September 1989.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Angeles, a Los Angeles investment management concern, said
that company officials weren't available to discuss the
agreement. It said it expects the agreement to be finalized
by early next month.
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   ANGELES Corp. said its agreement to acquire a three-year
option to buy 22% of its common and other securities from
certain former owners of Quinoco Cos. involves an exercise
price for the option of $30 million. Monday's edition
incorrectly said Angeles agreed to pay $30 million for the
option.
   (WSJ July 25, 1990)
